ce:section.ce:para:
The photovoltaic (PV) performance was investigated under 1 sun illumination level of 100 mW/cm2. Fig. 11 and Table 1 present the J-V curves and PV parameters obtained from three TiO2-DSSCs. The TiO2-DSSC with a mixture of GQD+N719 gained the highest Voc of 0.75 V, Jsc of 5.075 mA/cm2, and η of 3.011%. In contrast, the LBL sample generated a low Voc of 0.717 V with FF value of 62%. Since Voc is defined as the difference between the Fermi level of TiO2 and the redox potential of the electrolyte, Voc is diminished with a low number of electrons in the TiO2 photoanode layer [50]. In addition, the Jsc and η increase up to 34% and 28.73%, respectively, compared to the cell sensitized with N719 dye. The low Jsc obtained by the N719 sample is due to the less electron generated inside the cell. Whereby the DSSC generates less tri-iodide ions (
I 3 −
) at the surface of the counter electrode, this event influences the decrease of Jsc [51]. On the other hand, Kumar et al. reported that GQD has a similar role as the dye, generating electrons by a single photon [52]. This ability will infuse more electrons into the TiO2 photoelectrode and, therefore, improve Jsc and η of the DSSCs. Moreover, Mustafa and Sulaiman stated that TiO2 decorated with GQD performs as a light scattering layer (LSL), increases the optical path length, and increases incident light [53]. Hence, the LSL trapped extra light excites more dye molecules, produces more electrons (photocurrent), and increases the power conversion efficiency of the DSSC.
